<TITLE> Charges against Satkhira mutineers to be framed Jan 18 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Satkhira, Dec 08 (bdnews24.com)The special court in Satkhira on Tuesday set Jan 18 to frame charges against 60 BDR members accused of siding with the mutineers in the border guards' Peelkhana headquarters in Dhaka. The court set up in the 41 Rifles Battalion headquarters in the district set the date in presence of all 60personnel of 7 Rifles Battalion based in Neeldumur. Of them, 34 are in prison and 27 under the custody of the battalion in a mutiny case filed with Shyamnagar Police Station. They were produced before the court sometime before 10am. 7 Rifles Battalion commander lieutenant colonel Badrul Alam brought charges against them for breach of discipline, vandalism and looting under the BDR Act-1972. BDR director general Maj Gen Moinul Islam headed a three-member bench of judges. The two other judges were lieutenant colonel Gazi Khalid Hossain and Major Lutful Karim. The court adjourned at 11:05am, following which the defendants were taken back to prison. The trial of suspected BDR mutineers in Satkhira region began a day before, which is the second trial after the first BDR mutiny trial in a Rangamati court last month. The bloody Feb 25-26 mutiny at the Dhaka headquarters killed over 73 people, 57 of them army officers deputed to the paramilitary force. The rebellion also spread to other BDR posts around the country. On Nov 15, the government formed six special courts, including two in Dhaka, to try some 3,500 border guards accused in some 40 cases around the country. In the event of a guilty finding, the maximum penalty for rebellion is seven years in jail. The six special courts are trying charges of killings, looting and arson. There have been 31 cases filed across the country on charges related to the BDR mutiny. bdn
